import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

const pageContent = "<div style=\"margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;\" class=\"pages\"><div id=\"L1223406811\" page-url=\"4-days-in-valencia-itinerary\" class=\"page\"><a id=\"4-days-in-valencia-itinerary\"></a><div class=\"page-layout\"><div class=\"page-content\"><bodycopy style=\"--fit-height: 10px; --resize-parent-width: 100%;\"><!--  POST HERO  -->\n<section class=\"post-hero\">\n  <div class=\"post-route-strip\">\n    <span>Europe</span>&nbsp;· Spain · Valencia ·&nbsp;<span>Summer 2024</span>\n  </div>\n\n  <h1 class=\"post-hero-title\"><em>4 Days in Valencia:</em> Where the River Became a Garden</h1>\n  <p class=\"post-hero-sub\">Four days along a missing river — a flood turned into a nine-kilometre garden, Gothic silk at one end and Calatrava's white future at the other, and paella's true home.</p>\n  <div class=\"post-stats\">\n    <div class=\"stat\"><span class=\"stat-num\">4</span><span class=\"stat-label\">Days</span></div>\n    <div class=\"stat\"><span class=\"stat-num\">9km</span><span class=\"stat-label\">River-Garden</span></div>\n    <div class=\"stat\"><span class=\"stat-num\">Paella</span><span class=\"stat-label\">Birthplace</span></div>\n    <div class=\"stat\"><span class=\"stat-num\">~A$499</span><span class=\"stat-label\">4-Night Stay</span></div>\n  </div>\n</section>\n\n<!--  OPENING: THE ARRIVAL  -->\n<section class=\"opening-prose\">\n  <div class=\"narrative\">\n    <div class=\"prose\">\n      <p class=\"drop-cap\">Valencia has a river that isn't there, and that absence is the best idea any Spanish city ever had. The Turia ran through the heart of the city for a thousand years until, in 1957, it rose in a catastrophic flood that drowned the streets and killed dozens. The engineers' answer was drastic: they diverted the entire river around the south of the city, leaving its old bed — nine kilometres of it, curving right through the centre — empty and dry. The plan was to pave it into a motorway. The people of Valencia refused. <em>El riu és nostre i el volem verd</em>, they said — the river is ours and we want it green — and instead of a freeway the city got the <strong>Jardí del Túria</strong>, a nine-kilometre garden running through its middle where the water used to be: a sunken green ribbon of orange trees, fountains, sports pitches, palm groves and cycle paths, crossed by the same ancient stone bridges that once spanned the flood.</p>\n      <p>It is the most quietly radical thing in any city on the trip — a place that looked at a disaster and built a park out of the scar. And the garden tells the whole story of Valencia in a single walk: start at the old end, among the Gothic silk-exchange and the markets of the medieval trading city, and follow the green all the way to the far end, where Santiago Calatrava's blinding-white <strong>City of Arts and Sciences</strong> rises out of the old riverbed like a fleet of landed spaceships. A thousand years of the place, laid end to end along a missing river.</p>\n      <p>Four days here, and the city sorts itself by that green spine: the old silk town at one end, the white future at the other, the beaches and the rice fields off to the sea, and the garden tying it all together.</p>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n</section>\n\n<!--  CHAPTER I  -->\n<section class=\"chapter-break\">\n  <div class=\"narrative\">\n    <div class=\"chapter-number\">Chapter I</div>\n    <h2 class=\"chapter-name\"><em>The</em> Garden</h2>\n    <p class=\"chapter-epithet\">The Túria — a river turned into nine kilometres of green</p>\n\n    <div class=\"prose\">\n      <p>The best way to meet Valencia is to get down into the riverbed. The <strong>Jardí del Túria</strong> sits below street level, in the broad sunken channel the water carved, so that walking or cycling its length is to move through the city in a green trench, the traffic and the noise up on the banks and the garden cool and shaded below. Hire a bike — the city is flat and the garden is a continuous traffic-free path — and ride the whole nine kilometres, passing under the old bridges, through the orange groves and rose gardens and the great Gulliver playground where children swarm over a giant reclining figure. It is where Valencia actually lives: joggers and dog-walkers and families and old men playing pétanque, the daily life of the city poured into the space a flood once filled.</p>\n      <p>The story under it is the point. A city that suffered a disaster, refused the obvious concrete solution, and chose instead to give the wound back to its people as something green and useful — there are not many better arguments for what a city can be. The garden is free, always open, and the single best thing Valencia has done. The traveller could skip every monument and museum and simply ride the Túria end to end, and would still understand the place. Everything else in the city hangs off this green line like fruit off a branch.</p>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <aside class=\"pull\">\n    <p>A place that looked at a disaster and built a park out of the scar.</p>\n  </aside>\n</section>\n\n<!--  CHAPTER II  -->\n<section class=\"chapter-break\">\n  <div class=\"narrative\">\n    <div class=\"chapter-number\">Chapter II</div>\n    <h2 class=\"chapter-name\"><em>The</em> Silk City</h2>\n    <p class=\"chapter-epithet\">La Lonja, the markets, and the Holy Grail</p>\n\n    <div class=\"prose\">\n      <p>At the old end of the garden is the medieval city that the river once served — Valencia's golden age, when it grew rich on silk and trade. The proof stands in the <strong>Lonja de la Seda</strong>, the Silk Exchange, a masterpiece of civil Gothic architecture whose great hall of spiralling stone columns, twisting up like palm trunks into the vaults, is one of the most beautiful rooms in Spain and a UNESCO site in its own right. Across the way the <strong>Mercado Central</strong> carries the trade into the present: a vast Art Nouveau market hall of iron, glass and tile, one of the largest in Europe, where the produce of the <em>huerta</em> — Valencia's famously fertile market garden — is piled in glorious abundance under a ceramic dome. For a more genteel version there is the <strong>Mercado Colón</strong>, a modernista jewel now full of cafés, the right place for a mid-morning <em>horchata</em>.</p>\n      <p>And the <strong>Cathedral</strong> keeps the city's strangest claim. In a side chapel sits the <strong>Santo Cáliz</strong> — a plain agate cup that the Church recognises as a serious candidate for the actual Holy Grail, the cup of the Last Supper, brought west and hidden through centuries of war. Whether or not the traveller believes a word of it, there is something quietly extraordinary about a relic of that magnitude sitting almost unremarked in a working cathedral, with the <strong>Miguelete</strong> bell-tower to climb beside it for the view over the old-town roofs. Gothic silk money, a great market, and maybe the Grail — the medieval city packed all of it into a few walkable blocks at the head of the garden.</p>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n</section>\n\n<!--  CHAPTER III  -->\n<section class=\"chapter-break\">\n  <div class=\"narrative\">\n    <div class=\"chapter-number\">Chapter III</div>\n    <h2 class=\"chapter-name\"><em>The</em> White Future</h2>\n    <p class=\"chapter-epithet\">The City of Arts and Sciences at the other end of the river</p>\n\n    <div class=\"prose\">\n      <p>Follow the green the other way and the centuries fall away. At the seaward end of the riverbed, where the Turia once met the Mediterranean, the local architect <strong>Santiago Calatrava</strong> built the <strong>Ciudad de las Artes y las Ciencias</strong> — the City of Arts and Sciences — a complex of blinding-white structures set in shallow blue reflecting pools that looks less like a set of buildings than like something that landed. There is the eye-shaped <strong>Hemisfèric</strong> cinema, the skeletal <strong>Museu de les Ciències</strong> like the ribcage of a vast beached whale, the <strong>Palau de les Arts</strong> opera house under its great curved shell, and the long white promenade of the <strong>Umbracle</strong>. It is theatrical, divisive, expensive, and undeniably spectacular — the same civic ambition that turned a flood into a garden, expressed half a century later in titanium-white concrete.</p>\n      <p>At the far end sits <strong>L'Oceanogràfic</strong>, the largest aquarium in Europe, its buildings shaped like water lilies, holding everything from belugas and sharks to a walk-through ocean tunnel — the trip's one big-ticket family attraction, and worth a half-day. To stand in the reflecting pools at dusk, the white shells going pink and the whole thing doubled in the still water, is to see Valencia's defining trait in built form: a city unafraid of a grand gesture, that would rather build something astonishing than something safe. The medieval silk hall and the science-fiction opera house are the same impulse, five hundred years apart.</p>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n</section>\n\n<!--  CHAPTER IV  -->\n<section class=\"chapter-break\">\n  <div class=\"narrative\">\n    <div class=\"chapter-number\">Chapter IV</div>\n    <h2 class=\"chapter-name\"><em>The</em> Rice and the Sea</h2>\n    <p class=\"chapter-epithet\">Paella's true home, the beaches, and horchata</p>\n\n    <div class=\"prose\">\n      <p>There is one more thing Valencia is the birthplace of, and it is worth crossing the country to get right: <strong>paella</strong>. Not the yellow seafood tourist version, but the real <em>paella valenciana</em>, born in the rice paddies of the <strong>Albufera</strong> lagoon just south of the city — chicken, rabbit, runner beans, <em>garrofó</em>, saffron and short rice, cooked flat over orange-wood fire until the bottom forms the prized crust the locals call <em>socarrat</em>. Valencians are, with total justification, fierce about this; to eat paella where it was invented, made the way it was invented, is one of the trip's great meals. Take a cooking class and shop the Mercado Central for it, or eat it properly at lunchtime (never dinner — paella is a midday dish) out by the <strong>Malvarrosa</strong> beach, where the <em>barracas</em> have served rice by the sand for a century.</p>\n      <p>And the sea is right there. The long city beaches of <strong>Malvarrosa</strong> and <strong>Patacona</strong> run north from the old fishermen's quarter of <strong>El Cabanyal</strong> — a grid of low houses faced in bright broken tile, faded and beautiful and slowly being rediscovered. Inland at <strong>Alboraya</strong> they grow the <em>chufa</em> (tiger nut) that makes <strong>horchata</strong>, the cold sweet milky drink Valencia invented, best drunk with a sugar-crusted <em>fartón</em> to dip. Between the rice, the beach and the horchata, Valencia turns out to be a city you eat and drink as much as you look at — and then the fast train north, up the coast to Barcelona, and the last stop of the circuit.</p>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n</section>\n\n<div class=\"ornament\">· · · ✦ · · ·</div>\n\n<div class=\"beat\">Gothic silk at one end, a white future at the other, and the daily life of the city flowing green between.</div>\n\n<!--  PRACTICAL: GETTING THERE  -->\n<section class=\"practical\">\n  <div class=\"prac-header\">\n    <div class=\"prac-city\">Getting There &amp; Around</div>\n    <div class=\"prac-dates\">Valencia · Summer 2024</div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"prac-section\">\n    <div class=\"prac-label\">By Train</div>\n    <div class=\"prac-item\"><strong>From Madrid</strong> — fast trains in <strong>under 2 hours</strong> (roughly <strong>A$52</strong>), into Joaquín Sorolla.</div>\n    <div class=\"prac-item\"><strong>Onward to Barcelona</strong> — a fast <strong>train, about 3 hours</strong> (roughly <strong>A$111</strong>), up the Mediterranean coast.</div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"prac-section\">\n    <div class=\"prac-label\">Getting Around &amp; Staying</div>\n    <div class=\"prac-item\">Valencia is <strong>flat and made for cycling</strong> — rent a bike and use the Túria garden as your highway. The metro reaches the City of Arts, the beaches and the airport.</div>\n    <div class=\"prac-item\">The trip's Airbnb sat on <strong>Calle Torno del Hospital</strong>, near the Mercado Central. Roughly <strong>A$499 for four nights</strong>.</div>\n  </div>\n</section>\n\n<!--  PRACTICAL: SITES & TICKETS  -->\n<section class=\"practical\">\n  <div class=\"prac-header\">\n    <div class=\"prac-city\">Sites &amp; Tickets</div>\n    <div class=\"prac-dates\">Costs in AUD (€ locked)</div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"prac-section\">\n    <div class=\"prac-label\">Old Town</div>\n    <div class=\"prac-item\"><strong>Jardí del Túria</strong> — free, always open. The garden spine; ride it end to end.</div>\n    <div class=\"prac-item\"><strong>La Lonja de la Seda</strong> — about <strong>A$4 (€2)</strong>, free Sundays. <strong>Cathedral &amp; Santo Cáliz</strong> — around <strong>A$13 (€8)</strong> with audioguide.</div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"prac-section\">\n    <div class=\"prac-label\">City of Arts</div>\n    <div class=\"prac-item\">The plazas and pools are <strong>free to walk</strong>; the <strong>Oceanogràfic</strong> runs around <strong>A$60 (€36)</strong>, the science museum and Hemisfèric less. Combo tickets save money.</div>\n    <div class=\"prac-item\"><strong>Mercado Central &amp; Mercado Colón</strong> — free to enter; eat and drink your way through.</div>\n  </div>\n</section>\n\n<!--  PRACTICAL: EATING & DRINKING  -->\n<section class=\"practical\">\n  <div class=\"prac-header\">\n    <div class=\"prac-city\">Eating &amp; Drinking</div>\n    <div class=\"prac-dates\">The trip's table</div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"prac-section\">\n    <div class=\"prac-label\">The Rice</div>\n    <div class=\"prac-item\"><strong>Paella valenciana</strong> — the real thing (chicken, rabbit, beans), eaten at <strong>lunch</strong>, ideally out by Malvarrosa or toward the Albufera. Not the dinner-time seafood tourist version.</div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"prac-section\">\n    <div class=\"prac-label\">Dinner &amp; Drinks</div>\n    <div class=\"prac-item\"><strong>Karaki Gastro</strong> &amp; <strong>Meat Market</strong> — the modern dinners; book ahead. <strong>Restaurante Les Tendes</strong> — a relaxed old-town lunch.</div>\n    <div class=\"prac-item\"><strong>Horchata de chufa</strong> with a <em>fartón</em> to dip — the city's signature cold drink (a Vida or an Alboraya house). <strong>Agua de Valencia</strong> — the cava-and-orange cocktail, if the night calls for it.</div>\n  </div>\n</section>\n\n<!--  PRACTICAL: TIPS & WATCH-OUTS  -->\n<section class=\"practical\">\n  <div class=\"prac-header\">\n    <div class=\"prac-city\">Tips &amp; Watch-outs</div>\n    <div class=\"prac-dates\">For the four days</div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"prac-section\">\n    <div class=\"prac-label\">On the Ground</div>\n    <div class=\"tip-row\"><strong>Rent a bike and live in the Túria.</strong> Flat, traffic-free, and it connects everything from the old town to the City of Arts.</div>\n    <div class=\"tip-row\"><strong>Eat paella at lunch, and where it's made well.</strong> Locals don't eat it for dinner; the seafood version on the tourist drag isn't the real <em>valenciana</em>.</div>\n    <div class=\"tip-row\"><strong>Book the Oceanogràfic and combo tickets online</strong> — it's the City of Arts' big draw and queues build.</div>\n    <div class=\"tip-row\"><strong>El Cabanyal rewards a wander</strong> — the tiled fishermen's houses near the beach are a quiet pleasure.</div>\n    <div class=\"tip-row\"><strong>If you can, time it to Las Fallas (March)</strong> — Valencia's wild fire-and-fireworks festival is one of Europe's great spectacles.</div>\n  </div>\n</section>\n\n<!--  VIATOR TOURS  -->\n<div class=\"tours\">\n  <div class=\"tours-label\">Guided Experiences — Valencia</div>\n  <div class=\"tours-grid\">\n    <a class=\"tour-card\" href=\"https://www.viator.com/tours/Valencia/Paella-Cooking-Class-with-Valencia-Central-Market-Tour/d811-37016P9?pid=P00295455&amp;mcid=42383&amp;medium=link\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">\n      <div class=\"tour-type\">Cooking Class</div>\n      <div class=\"tour-name\">Paella Cooking Class with Central Market Tour</div>\n      <div class=\"tour-meta\">Shop the Mercado Central, then cook the real <em>valenciana</em> over the fire — paella in the city that invented it.</div>\n      <div class=\"tour-footer\">\n        <span class=\"tour-price\">From ~A$120</span>\n        <span class=\"tour-link-label\">View on Viator →</span>\n      </div>\n    </a>\n    <a class=\"tour-card\" href=\"https://www.viator.com/tours/Valencia/City-of-Arts-and-Sciences-and-Turias-Gardens-Bike-Tour/d811-213270P1?pid=P00295455&amp;mcid=42383&amp;medium=link\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">\n      <div class=\"tour-type\">Bike Tour</div>\n      <div class=\"tour-name\">Túria Gardens &amp; City of Arts Bike Tour</div>\n      <div class=\"tour-meta\">The whole green spine by bike — the sunken river-garden, the old bridges, and Calatrava's white future at the end.</div>\n      <div class=\"tour-footer\">\n        <span class=\"tour-price\">From ~A$45</span>\n        <span class=\"tour-link-label\">View on Viator →</span>\n      </div>\n    </a>\n    <a class=\"tour-card\" href=\"https://www.viator.com/Valencia-attractions/Valencia-Oceanografic-LOceanografic/d811-a15135?pid=P00295455&amp;mcid=42383&amp;medium=link\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">\n      <div class=\"tour-type\">Aquarium</div>\n      <div class=\"tour-name\">L'Oceanogràfic — Tickets &amp; Tours</div>\n      <div class=\"tour-meta\">Europe's largest aquarium, in water-lily buildings at the seaward end of the garden — belugas, sharks and an ocean tunnel.</div>\n      <div class=\"tour-footer\">\n        <span class=\"tour-price\">See Viator</span>\n        <span class=\"tour-link-label\">Browse on Viator →</span>\n      </div>\n    </a>\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n<!--  ITINERARY  -->\n<section class=\"itin-block\">\n  <div class=\"itin-inner\">\n    <div class=\"itin-block-title\">Four Days in Valencia at a Glance</div>\n\n    <p class=\"itin-meta\">Shape: <strong>a flat, bike-friendly city sorted by its river-garden — old silk town to white future</strong>.</p>\n    <p class=\"itin-meta\">Stay: <strong>old centre, ~A$499 / 4 nights</strong>.</p>\n\n    <div class=\"itin-section-head\">Valencia — along the missing river</div>\n    <div class=\"itin-days\">\n      <div class=\"itin-day-row\"><span class=\"itin-day-num\">Day 1</span>The old silk city: La Lonja, the Mercado Central, the Cathedral and the Santo Cáliz, the Miguelete; horchata at the Mercado Colón.</div>\n      <div class=\"itin-day-row\"><span class=\"itin-day-num\">Day 2</span>Rent a bike and ride the <strong>Jardí del Túria</strong> end to end, finishing at the <strong>City of Arts and Sciences</strong>; the pools at dusk.</div>\n      <div class=\"itin-day-row\"><span class=\"itin-day-num\">Day 3</span><strong>L'Oceanogràfic</strong> in the morning; the afternoon at <strong>Malvarrosa</strong> beach and the tiled streets of <strong>El Cabanyal</strong>; a proper paella lunch by the sand.</div>\n      <div class=\"itin-day-row\"><span class=\"itin-day-num\">Day 4</span>A paella cooking class and the markets, or out to <strong>Alboraya</strong> for horchata and <strong>Port Saplaya</strong>; then the fast train north to Barcelona.</div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n</section>\n\n<!--  CLOSING REFLECTION  -->\n<section class=\"post-closing\">\n  <div class=\"narrative\">\n    <div class=\"prose\">\n      <p>Valencia is the city that turned its worst day into its best feature, and there is something in that the whole trip keeps circling back to — the way a place reveals its character not in its monuments but in what it decides to do with what it's been given. A flood became a garden. A dry riverbed became the spine that holds a thousand years of the city together, with Gothic silk at one end and a white-concrete future at the other and the daily life of Valencia flowing green between them. It is not Spain's most famous city, and it is, quietly, one of its most likeable.</p>\n      <p>The traveller leaves it well-fed and faintly converted — on a bike returned, with the taste of real paella and cold horchata still about — and boards the last train of the circuit, north along the Mediterranean. Ahead lies Barcelona, the end of the line: Gaudí's unfinished argument, the sea, and the close of a thousand kilometres of overland road.</p>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n</section>\n\n<div class=\"beat\">But the road is ever onward.</div>\n\n<!--  FAQ  -->\n<section class=\"faq-block\">\n  <div class=\"faq-inner\">\n    <div class=\"faq-item\">\n      <div class=\"faq-q\">What are the must-do things in Valencia?</div>\n      <div class=\"faq-a\">Ride or walk the Jardí del Túria (the nine-kilometre garden in the old riverbed); see the Gothic Lonja de la Seda and the Mercado Central; visit the Cathedral and its claimed Holy Grail; explore Calatrava's City of Arts and Sciences and L'Oceanogràfic; eat real paella valenciana at lunch; and hit the Malvarrosa beach and the tiled El Cabanyal quarter.</div>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"faq-item\">\n      <div class=\"faq-q\">Why is there a garden where Valencia's river should be?</div>\n      <div class=\"faq-a\">After a catastrophic flood in 1957, the Turia river was diverted around the city. Rather than turn the dry riverbed into a motorway, Valencia made it the Jardí del Túria — a nine-kilometre sunken garden running through the centre, crossed by the old bridges. It's the city's signature, and free to enjoy.</div>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"faq-item\">\n      <div class=\"faq-q\">Where do you eat real paella in Valencia?</div>\n      <div class=\"faq-a\">Paella was born in the Albufera rice paddies south of Valencia, and the authentic paella valenciana uses chicken, rabbit and beans — not seafood. Eat it at lunch (never dinner), ideally out by Malvarrosa beach or toward the Albufera, or learn to make it in a cooking class with a Central Market shop.</div>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"faq-item\">\n      <div class=\"faq-q\">Is the City of Arts and Sciences worth visiting?</div>\n      <div class=\"faq-a\">Yes — it's Valencia's spectacular modern landmark, a complex of futuristic white buildings by Santiago Calatrava set in reflecting pools at the seaward end of the riverbed. The plazas are free to walk; the standout paid attraction is L'Oceanogràfic, the largest aquarium in Europe.</div>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"faq-item\">\n      <div class=\"faq-q\">How many days do you need in Valencia?</div>\n      <div class=\"faq-a\">Three to four. That covers the old silk-trade centre and markets, a full ride along the Túria garden to the City of Arts, the Oceanogràfic, the beaches and El Cabanyal, and a proper paella — without rushing. Valencia is flat and bike-friendly, so you cover a lot easily.</div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n</section>\n\n\n\n<!--  FURTHER READING  -->\n<section class=\"next-chronicles\">\n  <div class=\"narrative\">\n    <h2 class=\"chapter-name\" style=\"text-align:center; margin-bottom: 2.5rem;\"><em>Further</em> Reading</h2>\n    <div class=\"posts-grid\">\n      <a class=\"post-card\" href=\"/7-days-in-barcelona/\">\n        <div class=\"post-region\">Spain · Catalonia</div>\n        <div class=\"post-title\">Barcelona: Gaudí's Unfinished Argument</div>\n        <div class=\"post-excerpt\">The end of the line — the Sagrada Família, the sea, and the close of the overland circuit.</div>\n      <div class=\"post-meta\">7 days&nbsp;<span class=\"dot\"></span>&nbsp;City Guide</div>\n      </a>\n      <a class=\"post-card\" href=\"/3-days-in-madrid-the-capital-at-full-volume/\">\n        <div class=\"post-region\">Spain · Madrid</div>\n        <div class=\"post-title\">Madrid: The Capital at Full Volume</div>\n        <div class=\"post-excerpt\">The stop before the coast — the oldest restaurant on earth, Guernica, and appetite as evidence of life.</div>\n      <div class=\"post-meta\">3 days&nbsp;<span class=\"dot\"></span>&nbsp;City Guide</div>\n      </a>\n      <a class=\"post-card\" href=\"/4-weeks-portugal-to-spain-by-rail-road/\">\n        <div class=\"post-region\">Iberia · Circuit</div>\n        <div class=\"post-title\">Portugal to Spain by Rail and Road</div>\n        <div class=\"post-excerpt\">The full thirty-day circuit — Porto to Barcelona, almost entirely overland, with the costs laid bare.</div>\n      <div class=\"post-meta\">4 weeks&nbsp;<span class=\"dot\"></span>&nbsp;Chronicle</div>\n      </a>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n</section></bodycopy></div></div></div></div>";
const schema = {"@context": "https://schema.org", "@graph": [{"@type": "Article", "headline": "4 Days in Valencia Itinerary", "description": "A four-day Valencia itinerary — the Turia gardens, the Gothic silk exchange, Calatrava's City of Arts and Sciences, and the true home of paella.", "author": {"@type": "Person", "name": "Mitch Chadban"}, "publisher": {"@type": "Organization", "name": "There & Back Again", "url": "https://travel.mitchchadban.com/"}, "mainEntityOfPage": {"@type": "WebPage", "@id": "https://travel.mitchchadban.com/4-days-in-valencia-itinerary/"}, "url": "https://travel.mitchchadban.com/4-days-in-valencia-itinerary/", "inLanguage": "en-AU"}, {"@type": "BreadcrumbList", "itemListElement": [{"@type": "ListItem", "position": 1, "name": "Home", "item": "https://travel.mitchchadban.com/"}, {"@type": "ListItem", "position": 2, "name": "Chronicles", "item": "https://travel.mitchchadban.com/chronicles/"}, {"@type": "ListItem", "position": 3, "name": "4 Days in Valencia Itinerary", "item": "https://travel.mitchchadban.com/4-days-in-valencia-itinerary/"}]}, {"@type": "FAQPage", "mainEntity": [{"@type": "Question", "name": "What are the must-do things in Valencia?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Ride or walk the Jardí del Túria (the nine-kilometre garden in the old riverbed); see the Gothic Lonja de la Seda and the Mercado Central; visit the Cathedral and its claimed Holy Grail; explore Calatrava's City of Arts and Sciences and L'Oceanogràfic; eat real paella valenciana at lunch; and hit the Malvarrosa beach and the tiled El Cabanyal quarter."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "Why is there a garden where Valencia's river should be?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "After a catastrophic flood in 1957, the Turia river was diverted around the city. Rather than turn the dry riverbed into a motorway, Valencia made it the Jardí del Túria — a nine-kilometre sunken garden running through the centre, crossed by the old bridges. It's the city's signature, and free to enjoy."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "Where do you eat real paella in Valencia?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Paella was born in the Albufera rice paddies south of Valencia, and the authentic paella valenciana uses chicken, rabbit and beans — not seafood. Eat it at lunch (never dinner), ideally out by Malvarrosa beach or toward the Albufera, or learn to make it in a cooking class with a Central Market shop."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "Is the City of Arts and Sciences worth visiting?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Yes — it's Valencia's spectacular modern landmark, a complex of futuristic white buildings by Santiago Calatrava set in reflecting pools at the seaward end of the riverbed. The plazas are free to walk; the standout paid attraction is L'Oceanogràfic, the largest aquarium in Europe."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "How many days do you need in Valencia?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Three to four. That covers the old silk-trade centre and markets, a full ride along the Túria garden to the City of Arts, the Oceanogràfic, the beaches and El Cabanyal, and a proper paella — without rushing. Valencia is flat and bike-friendly, so you cover a lot easily."}}]}]};
